[
    {
        "content": "<p>Does there exists an appropriate <em>smooth version</em> of  Dold-Kan correspondence  in the existing literature?</p>",
        "id": 248404114,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628108966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Smooth in what sense?</p>",
        "id": 248405381,
        "sender_full_name": "Ben MacAdam",
        "timestamp": 1628109322
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Smooth in the sense of simplicial abelian Lie groups.</p>",
        "id": 248405644,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628109442
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well the correspondence works for any abelian category of which there are 'smooth versions' such as sheaves of modules on manifolds, if thats what you want.</p>",
        "id": 248405661,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1628109448
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Basically, I am interested to know what does the simplicial abelian Lie groups  correspond to \"in terms of chain complexes\"?</p>",
        "id": 248406016,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628109593
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, following on <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"341237\">@Fawzi Hreiki</span>  if you take a reasonable embedding of smooth manifolds into a locally presentable category (like the Dubuc topos or the microlinear objects in the Dubuc topos),  you'll get the usual Dold-Kan correspondence. I suppose you could then take the pointwise Lie derivative and get a simplicial Lie algebra?</p>",
        "id": 248406244,
        "sender_full_name": "Ben MacAdam",
        "timestamp": 1628109686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"318500\">ADITTYA CHAUDHURI</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Smooth.20version.20of.20Dold-Kan.20correspondence/near/248405644\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Smooth in the sense of simplicial abelian Lie groups.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmm, I'm not sure if the category of abelian Lie groups actually is abelian. I think this comes down to the fact that the category of smooth manifolds isn't all that nice.</p>",
        "id": 248406454,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1628109806
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ok.. But is there a \"good\"  category  which captures  \"Abelian property\"  and  \"smoothness\" simultaneously?  For example we often incorporate cocompleteness and completenss into the category of smooth manifolds by embedding them into the category of generalized smooth spaces like diffeological spaces?</p>",
        "id": 248406782,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628109997
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sure - any category of abelian group objects in a topos</p>",
        "id": 248406818,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1628110019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ohh! yes</p>",
        "id": 248406834,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628110030
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or any category of modules over a ring object in a topos</p>",
        "id": 248406845,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1628110037
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, my original question makes sense only after embedding into an appropriate category.. Am i right?</p>",
        "id": 248407024,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628110142
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>According to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/simplicial+Lie+algebra\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/simplicial+Lie+algebra</a> it seems  that at least in the  Lie algebra level, simplicial Lie algebras corresponds to dg-Lie algebras? Though I am not sure whether I am understanding it correctly!!</p>",
        "id": 248410399,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628111844
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, you can turn a simplicial Lie algebra into a differential graded Lie algebra, and conversely.</p>",
        "id": 248426889,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628124381
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's an adjunction between the category of simplicial Lie algebras and the category of dg Lie algebras.   But it's not an equivalence of categories.   With some extra conditions you can get a \"Quillen equivalence\" - the nLab states a theorem along these lines due to Quillen.</p>",
        "id": 248427321,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628124874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Smooth.20version.20of.20Dold-Kan.20correspondence/near/248406454\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hmm, I'm not sure if the category of abelian Lie groups actually is abelian. I think this comes down to the fact that the category of smooth manifolds isn't all that nice.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Right, the category of abelian Lie groups is not an abelian category.  Take a Lie group homomorphism </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi>S</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>S</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: \\mathbb{R} \\to S^1 \\times S^1 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.897438em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>that wraps the real line around the torus <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>S</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>S</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> S^1 \\times S^1 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.897438em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> with an irrational slope.   This is a monomorphism in the category of abelian Lie groups, and also an epimorphism (because its range is dense), yet not an isomorphism - which is impossible in an abelian category.</p>",
        "id": 248428834,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628126814
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>While the functor from chain complexes to simplicial abelian groups lifts to work for everything internal to manifolds (and indeed, probably internal to any category with finite products), the functor the other way is less clear. One needs to take the intersection of a bunch of kernels, and it's not immediate this is a manifold (it may be, I haven't checked). Much as for Lie 2-groups, where one wants to make sure that the groupoid internal to manifolds is in fact a Lie groupoid (so that source and target are submersions), some niceness might need to be assumed. Further, even when dealing with crossed modules of Lie groups, people often want to assume extra niceness, like the existence of smooth local sections of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G\\to H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>, or even just the existence of a smooth section on a neighbourhood of the identity of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I'm pretty sure that one doesn't need an abelian category, though, for Dold–Kan to work. I mean, it works for the semiabelian context too, with simplicial groups and a nonabelian version of chain complexes. The question is what happens when internalising. Working out the 2- or 3-term version would be instructive, I think.</p>",
        "id": 248434614,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1628134155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, David!  I dodged the main question because I wasn't up to figuring out exactly what was needed of a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> for Dold-Kan to work internal to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.   It's just a matter of going through the proof and seeing what one uses.  But it takes a bit of time.</p>",
        "id": 248438397,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1628139460
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The fact that Dold–Kan works for abelian groups tells us that the simplex category and the \"free cochain complex\" category are Morita equivalent, so that should imply it works for any Cauchy-complete additive category whatsoever.</p>",
        "id": 248438955,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhen Lin Low",
        "timestamp": 1628139898
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276422\">@David Michael Roberts</span> Thanks I will work through as you said. You mentioned \"non abelian version of chain complexes\", I am not much familiar with such objects. It seems they are pretty interesting. Can you suggest some references in that direction?</p>",
        "id": 248441822,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628143750
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"416301\">Zhen Lin Low</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Smooth.20version.20of.20Dold-Kan.20correspondence/near/248438955\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The fact that Dold–Kan works for abelian groups tells us that the simplex category and the \"free cochain complex\" category are Morita equivalent, so that should imply it works for any Cauchy-complete additive category whatsoever.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thank you .\"The fact that Dold–Kan works for abelian groups tells us that the simplex category and the \"free cochain complex\" category are Morita equivalent\" . This fact seems interesting. Can you suggest some references where such result is mentioned or anything in that direction?</p>",
        "id": 248441989,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628143953
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> Thank you!</p>",
        "id": 248442041,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628144039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"318500\">@ADITTYA CHAUDHURI</span>  See here: <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/hypercrossed+complex\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/hypercrossed+complex</a> (ignore the group(oid) stuff, just think about groups) and the links with Moore complexes</p>",
        "id": 248442756,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1628144888
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>like the existence of smooth local sections of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G\\to H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span>, or even just the existence of a smooth section on a neighbourhood of the identity of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>whoops, I meant local sections of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G\\to t(G)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111111111111111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333333333333333em\"/><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t\\colon G\\to H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111111111111111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333333333333333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> is the crossed module (and similarly for a nhd of the identity of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t(G)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>). In general, of course, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.61508em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> is not even surjective!</p>",
        "id": 248442854,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1628145017
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I agree that working with simplicial abelian groups internal a pretopos, say, or even perhaps just an exact category (<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/exact+category\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/exact+category</a>), might be enough to get some form of an internal Dold–Kan equivalence. Maybe less. </p>\n<p>Embedding the category of manifolds into that of diffeological spaces means all the nice constructions one wants will be available, as the latter is a quasitopos. But most people would just go all the way and embed simplicial abelian groups into oo-sheaves (on Mfld) of simplicial abelian groups, I guess.</p>",
        "id": 248443228,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1628145516
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276422\">@David Michael Roberts</span>  Thanks a lot!</p>",
        "id": 248443606,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1628146013
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The Dold–Kan correspondence works in any idempotent-complete additive category.  For a proof, see Theorem 1.2.3.7 in Lurie's Higher Algebra.  The category of abelian Lie groups is idempotent-complete.  So are many other bigger categories, e.g., sheaves of abelian groups on the site of smooth manifolds.</p>",
        "id": 249916536,
        "sender_full_name": "Dmitri Pavlov",
        "timestamp": 1629323554
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"408784\">@Dmitri Pavlov</span>  Thanks a lot!</p>",
        "id": 250052794,
        "sender_full_name": "ADITTYA CHAUDHURI",
        "timestamp": 1629409147
    }
